<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class=""><i><a href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939646,00.html" class="external text" title="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939646,00.html" rel="nofollow">Mixed Fiction</a></i>. <a href="/wiki/Time" title="Time">Time, Inc.</a>. <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1960-02-22"><a href="/wiki/1960" title="1960">1960</a>-<a href="/wiki/February_22" title="February 22">02-22</a></span><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939646,00.html" class="external free" title="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939646,00.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,939646,00.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-12-08</span>.  "Author Miller proves himself chillingly effective at communicating a kind of post-human lunar landscape of disaster. His faith in religious faith is commendable but not compelling. It is difficult to tell whether he believes that better bomb shelters or more Roman Catholics are the hope of the world. On the flyleaf of Canticle for Leibowitz, Novelist Miller writes, "A dedication is only a scratch where it itches." Intellectually speaking, so is his book.".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Mixed+Fiction&amp;rft.date=%5B%5B1960-02-22%5D%5D&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BTime%7CTime%2C+Inc.%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.time.com%2Ftime%2Fmagazine%2Farticle%2F0%2C9171%2C939646%2C00.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:A_Canticle_for_Leibowitz"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
